{"timestamp": "2025-12-04 12:48:48.728531", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting Diagnosis Report\n\nSummary of Network and Goal\n- Topology: host_1 — switch_1 — switch_2 — host_2, with bmv2 switches running a bloom-filter P4 program.\n- Hosts: host_1 (10.0.0.1, MAC 00:00:0a:00:00:01), host_2 (10.0.0.2, MAC 00:00:0a:00:00:02).\n- Objective: Assess network health, detect anomalies, localize faulty elements, and identify root cause.\n\nKey Tests Performed and Observations\n1) End-to-end reachability\n- Ping host_1 -> host_2: timeout.\n- Ping host_2 -> host_1: timeout.\n- Anomaly detected: complete loss of L3 connectivity between hosts.\n\n2) Host interface and routing state\n- host_1 eth0 up with 10.0.0.1/24; route 10.0.0.0/24 via eth0.\n- host_2 eth0 up with 10.0.0.2/24; route 10.0.0.0/24 via eth0.\n- ARP/neighbor entries are static/permanent:\n  - On host_1: 10.0.0.2 → 00:00:0a:00:00:02\n  - On host_2: 10.0.0.1 → 00:00:0a:00:00:01\n- Host RX/TX counters show a handful of frames observed, consistent with attempted pings.\n\n3) Switch behavior from bmv2 logs\n- Traffic clearly traverses the inter-switch link:\n  - switch_2 transmits out port 2; switch_1 receives on port 2.\n  - switch_1 then transmits to port 1 (toward host_1).\n- The ingress pipeline processes IPv4 and applies MyIngress.ipv4_lpm with hits (not misses).\n- Crucial action parameters observed in logs:\n  - On switch_1, for dst IP 10.0.0.1 (0a000001): Action MyIngress.ipv4_forward - 66660a666601,1\n    - dst MAC applied: 66:66:0a:66:66:01 (non-standard, not host_1’s MAC)\n  - On switch_2, for dst IP 10.0.0.1 (0a000001): Action MyIngress.ipv4_forward - a000001,2\n    - dst “MAC” argument appears as a 32-bit IPv4 hex (0x0a000001) rather than a 48-bit MAC address; when interpreted as a MAC it would not match host_1’s NIC.\n- The P4 action code performs L3 forwarding semantics (rewriting Ethernet dst/src and decrementing TTL), so the dstAddr parameter must be the correct 48-bit next-hop MAC.\n\nDiagnosis\n\n1) Anomaly Detection\n- End-to-end connectivity failure (ping timeouts both directions).\n\n2) Fault Localization\n- Physical links and switch pipelines are functioning: packets are received, parsed, matched in LPM, and transmitted out expected egress ports across the inter-switch link and toward the hosts.\n- Hosts are correctly configured, links up, and ARP entries present.\n- The fault is within the control-plane/table programming on both bmv2 switches (MyIngress.ipv4_lpm entries), specifically the action parameters used for MAC rewriting.\n\n3) Root Cause Identification\n- MyIngress.ipv4_lpm entries are programmed with incorrect dst MACs for the MyIngress.ipv4_forward action:\n  - One switch uses a non-sensical MAC 66:66:0a:66:66:01.\n  - The other uses a 32-bit IPv4 value (0x0a000001) where a 48-bit MAC is required.\n- As a result, frames forwarded toward the hosts carry incorrect destination MAC addresses and are dropped by the hosts, preventing ICMP echo/reply exchange.\n- Evidence:\n  - bmv2 logs show the actual action parameters (“ipv4_forward - 66660a666601,1,” and “ipv4_forward - a000001,2,”) which do not match host NIC MACs (00:00:0a:00:00:01 / 00:00:0a:00:00:02).\n  - Despite correct LPM hits and expected egress ports, connectivity fails—consistent with L2 mismatch on final hop.\n\nAdditional Notes\n- Attempts to dump switch tables via the table dump tool encountered a syntax error in the wrapper, but bmv2 logs were sufficient to confirm entries and parameters.\n- No evidence of port down, routing miss, or checksum/TTL issues; issue is limited to MAC rewrite values in LPM action data.\n\nConclusion\n- Network health: Degraded; end-to-end L3 connectivity is broken.\n- Faulty components: Control-plane entries in MyIngress.ipv4_lpm on switch_1 and switch_2.\n- Root cause: Misconfigured MyIngress.ipv4_forward action parameters (incorrect next-hop MAC addresses), causing final-hop frames to have wrong Ethernet destination MAC and be dropped by hosts.